uction","Inhibits dihydrofolate reductase","Suppresses B cell antibody production","Prevents T cell activation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of dihydrofolate reductase\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of methotrexate. This leads to decreased synthesis of purines and pyrimidines, which reduces DNA and RNA synthesis in rapidly dividing cells, including immune cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking tumour necrosis factor alpha\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of biological DMARDs like adalimumab.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of interleukin-1 production\u003C/strong\u003E may occur but is not the primary mechanism of methotrexate. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppression of B cell antibody production\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprevention of T cell activation\u003C/strong\u003E are secondary effects that occur as a result of the drug\u0027s primary mechanism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy inhibiting dihydrofolate reductase, methotrexate reduces the availability of folate-dependent one-carbon transfers required for purine and pyrimidine synthesis. This particularly affects rapidly dividing cells involved in the inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Disease-modifying antirheumatic drugs (DMARDs) work by suppressing the immune system to reduce inflammation and prevent joint damage in rheumatoid arthritis.","Methotrexate inhibits dihydrofolate reductase, reducing DNA and RNA synthesis in rapidly dividing immune cells.","Regular monitoring of liver function and blood counts is essential for patients taking DMARDs due to potential toxicity."],"references":["Stimulation of mucus productionTherapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), 